      {
        "id": 2548342,
        "name": "Maxwell A.",
        "username": "Maxwell_A",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/67e7ee/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2018-12-30T05:22:34.000Z",
        "cooked": "<ol>\n<li>\n<p>I\u2019ve had good luck with 2013 white burgundy. I think a lot of people have a very negative impression due to the very difficult weather conditions and the fact that it\u2019s an unpopular style in that it\u2019s leaner and more high acid. Yes, you still have to be selective as a lot depends on the vineyard decisions and quality of the wine producer but there are some excellent wines in this vintage.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>I had the pleasure of drinking a bottle of Niellon\u2019s Batard-Montrachet 2013 this past summer. I think the leaner and high acid style is a good match for Batard as the wines can sometimes be a bit richer and fatter for my taste in other vintages (also depending on producer). The wine was young of course, and opened up as I drank it over 2 days. Pretty closed and quiet at first but once it opened up it was gorgeous. Lots of structure but no fattness. Full but with the freshness of the 2013 vintage to carry all the material and make the finish keep going and going. I don\u2019t remember there being any signs of botrytis in this wine. I\u2019d absolutely love to see how this would be in 20-30 years but I don\u2019t have any in the cellar and I don\u2019t think I\u2019d want to deal with the premox risk if I did.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>",
        "post_number": 9,
